Hey, so there are now actually 3 subnets (as far as I'm aware) doing Distributed Training (DT). SN3, SN38 and SN9.

In standard ML training there are usually 2 ways to distribute the training process: 1) Data Parallelization (splitting the data across ndoes) 2) Model Parallelization (splitting the model across nodes).

SN3 and SN38 are doing 1 where each miner hosts a full version of the model and miners average their model states / gradients at various intervals whereas SN9 is attempting to do 1 and 2 where each miner only hosts a layer of the model.

There have been many exciting advancements within the Data Parallelisation field to try and reduce the communication overhead that has historically been it's biggest bottleneck. DeMo: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2411.19870 being one and DiLoCo: https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.07852 being another. SN38 is using the DiLoCo protocol whereas SN3 is using DeMo.

Run 5's nice progress continues with miners reaching an average loss of 3.7 compared to 4.7 last Friday (screenshot 1).

On Thursday we identified that the default Bittensor Dendrite built on top of aiohttp has a maximum connection limit of 100 by default which meant that only 100 UIDs were receving the AllReduce call instanteously whilst the other UIDs were receiving delayed calls. @distributed・38  over the last 2 weeks we discovered that our current scoring mechanism was not able to correctly penalise miners training on incorrect subsets of the data. We also discovered that miners achieving the lowest loss on unseen sections of the dataset weren't always at the top of the incentive curve. As we've investigated this further we found this to be due to two main reasons:

1. Our incentive mechanism was rewarding fast uploads as a proxy for how effective miners were at training. By focusing on this secondary metric we found that some miners were targeting methods to achieve faster upload intervals that were harmful to the primary objective we have - reducing their model's loss on unseen data.
2. We were using cosine similarity to compare the validator's model weights after training on the same dataset with miner's uploaded model weights. More detailed testing has shown us that this isn't a very effective validation mechanism during the later stages of training when changes in the model weights become very small. At these stages of training we found the differences in cosine similarity scores between miners training on their assigned data vs random / no new data to be indistinguishable.

Today, we're merging: https://github.com/dstrbtd/DistributedTraining/pull/71 which we've found to be successful in addressing these issues as well as a few more system enhancements:

1. Taking inspiration from Templar's Gauntlet, validators now evaluate a miner's performance by applying their published pseudo gradients to the global model and evaluating how much these reduce the global model's average loss
2. Ranking miners' loss reduction capabilities using the OpenSkill library
3. Reducing `local_batch_size_train_effective` from 2048 to 512
4. Increasing the outer optimiser learning rate to 1.0 to match the scaling laws of  https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.09799
5. Replacing the contents of `self.uid_tracker` with a cleaner, simplified data model. Miners' incentive are still based off total.score which is calculated using `total.score` = (75% x `train.score`) + (25% x `all_reduce.score`). However `train.score` is now based off (`train.random.score` x `train.assigned.score`). All these new scores will start appearing on wandb now.
6. Sets quantisation to False by default when compressing pseudo gradients

This take us up to `v1.1.8`. We're also restarted our current run to take us up to `run 6`.

Miners / Validators that aren't running with auto-updates please update to this latest version as soon as you can.

As mentioned yesterday, miners experiencing HuggingFace storage limits should take this transition to a new run as an opportunity to delete their current repos and create new ones to reduce their overall account storage. Miners running multiple miners should ideally limit 4 miners per each HF account.

Going forwards we'll be looking to reduce the size of the data we upload to tackle this HF issue and streaming validator logs to Grafana so that miners can easily dive into the metrics that are impacting their overall incentive.
